  "concepts": [
    {
      "id": "bank_as_middleman",
      "title": "The Bank as a Middleman",
      "summary": "A bank's most basic job is to sit between two groups of people: those who have money they are not using right now, and those who need money they do not have yet. The people with money deposit it in savings accounts. The bank takes that money and lends it to people who need a mortgage, a car loan, or business financing. The depositor gets a small return for letting the bank use their money. The borrower pays a higher rate for access to funds they need. The bank keeps the difference. That gap between what it pays depositors and what it charges borrowers is where most of a bank's profit comes from. Everything else a bank does — the app, the branches, the credit cards — is built on top of this simple act of connecting savers to borrowers.",
      "sections": [
        {
          "title": "Context",
          "body": [
            "Before banks existed, someone who needed money had to find a willing lender themselves. Someone with savings had no easy way to earn a return on idle funds. Banks solved both problems at once by creating a reliable place where money could flow from people who have it to people who need it.",
            "This middleman role is what makes banks useful to society. They collect small deposits from millions of people and pool that money into large loans that individuals or businesses could never arrange on their own."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Key figures forces",
          "body": [
            "The two key forces are depositors on one side and borrowers on the other. Depositors want safety and a return. Borrowers want access to funds at a manageable cost. The bank manages both relationships simultaneously and profits from the spread between them.",
            "Trust is also a critical force. Depositors only leave their money with a bank if they believe it will be there when they want it back. That trust is what makes the whole system work."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Core idea",
          "body": [
            "A bank makes money by charging borrowers more than it pays depositors. If it pays 2% on savings and charges 7% on loans, the 5% difference is its gross income before expenses. That spread, multiplied across billions of dollars in deposits and loans, is enormous.",
