      "id": "net_interest_margin",
      "title": "The Interest Rate Spread",
      "summary": "The single most important number in a bank's business is the gap between what it pays to borrow money and what it charges to lend it. This gap is called the net interest margin. If a bank pays depositors 2% and charges mortgage borrowers 7%, it earns a 5% spread on every dollar it has deployed. Multiply that across tens of billions of dollars in loans and the income is massive. Banks obsess over this spread because it is their core engine. When interest rates rise, the spread can widen and banks often profit more. When rates fall or competition heats up, the spread compresses and profits shrink. Understanding this one idea explains most of what banks do and most of how they think.",
      "sections": [
        {
          "title": "Context",
          "body": [
            "Banks have been earning money this way for centuries. The terminology changes, the products change, and the scale grows, but the underlying logic is always the same: charge more for money than you pay for it.",
