    {
      "id": "bank_regulation",
      "title": "How Banks Are Regulated",
      "summary": "Banks are in the business of taking risks to make money. Left completely unchecked, a bank has every incentive to lend aggressively, pay depositors as little as possible, and chase the highest returns it can find. That works well when the economy is strong. But when things go wrong, an overleveraged bank can collapse quickly, and because millions of ordinary people have their savings there, the damage spreads far beyond the bank itself. Regulation exists to manage that tension. Rules like capital requirements force banks to keep enough of their own money at risk so they have a cushion when loans go bad. Deposit insurance like the FDIC protects savers so a single bank failure does not cause a panic. The goal is not to stop banks from being profitable — it is to make sure their pursuit of profit does not blow up the whole system.",
      "sections": [
        {
          "title": "Context",
          "body": [
            "Before modern bank regulation, bank failures were common and devastating. A rumor that a bank was in trouble could trigger a run, where every depositor tried to withdraw at once, guaranteeing the collapse the rumor predicted. The Great Depression saw thousands of bank failures that wiped out ordinary savings and deepened the economic crisis.",
            "The regulatory system that exists today was built largely in response to those failures. Each major financial crisis, including the 2008 financial crisis, produced new rules designed to close the gaps that the previous disaster revealed."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Key figures forces",
          "body": [
            "The central tension is between profitability and stability. Banks want to maximize returns, which usually means lending more and holding less in reserve. Regulators want banks to hold enough capital to absorb losses without failing. These goals are in permanent conflict.",
            "Key regulatory tools include capital requirements, which force banks to fund a portion of their assets with equity rather than debt. Reserve requirements historically limited how much banks could lend relative to deposits. Deposit insurance removes the incentive for depositors to panic, which prevents runs."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Core idea",
          "body": [
            "Regulation is a guardrail, not a cage. It does not stop banks from being aggressive about profits. It just requires them to keep enough of their own money on the line so that when bets go wrong, the bank absorbs the loss instead of passing it on to depositors or taxpayers.",
            "The 2008 financial crisis is the clearest modern example of what happens when those guardrails are too weak. Banks had taken enormous risks funded mostly by borrowed money, with very little equity cushion. When mortgage values collapsed, there was nothing to absorb the losses and the system nearly froze."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Actions / how it works",
          "body": [
            "Capital requirements, shaped by international rules called the Basel Accords, require banks to hold a minimum percentage of their own equity relative to their risk-weighted assets. The riskier the loan book, the more equity the bank must hold. This limits how much risk a bank can take relative to the capital it has.",
            "The FDIC insures deposits up to $250,000 per account, which means ordinary savers do not need to monitor their bank's health. That removes the incentive for bank runs, which are often self-fulfilling."
