    {
      "id": "fractional_reserve",
      "title": "Fractional Reserve Banking",
      "summary": "When you deposit $1,000 in a bank, you might assume the bank holds all of it in a vault waiting for you. It does not. The bank keeps only a fraction of your deposit in reserve and lends the rest out. That loan gets deposited into another bank, which lends most of it out again. The same dollar gets multiplied across the system into many times its original value in loans. This is called fractional reserve banking, and it is how a relatively small pool of real deposits supports a much larger pool of credit in the economy. It is also why bank runs are so dangerous: if everyone asks for their money at once, the bank physically cannot return it all, because most of it has been lent out.",
      "sections": [
