    {
      "id": "equity_vs_borrowing",
      "title": "How Banks Fund Themselves",
      "summary": "To lend money, a bank first has to get money from somewhere. It has three main sources: deposits from customers, borrowing from other banks or financial markets, and equity raised from shareholders. Deposits are the cheapest and most stable source because customers accept low rates in exchange for safety and convenience. Borrowed funds from wholesale markets are more expensive and can dry up quickly in a crisis. Equity is the most expensive because shareholders expect high returns, but it is also the safest cushion because equity absorbs losses without triggering default. The mix of these three sources is called the bank's capital structure, and getting it right is one of the most important and consequential decisions a bank makes. Too much borrowed funding and the bank is fragile. Too much equity and it is inefficient.",
      "sections": [
        {
          "title": "Context",
          "body": [
            "Banks are unusual businesses because their raw material is money itself. Unlike a manufacturer that buys steel and sells cars, a bank borrows money at one price and lends it at another. That means how it funds itself is inseparable from its core business model.",
            "The 2008 financial crisis was in large part a story of banks that had funded themselves too heavily with short-term borrowing and too little equity. When those funding markets froze, banks with thin capital buffers had no room to absorb losses."
