    {
      "id": "types_of_banks",
      "title": "Different Types of Banks",
      "summary": "Not all banks work the same way or make money the same way. A commercial bank takes deposits and makes loans to individuals and businesses. An investment bank helps companies raise money by issuing stocks and bonds, advises on mergers, and trades financial instruments for its own account. A credit union is a member-owned cooperative that operates like a bank but returns profits to members rather than shareholders, usually in the form of lower loan rates and higher deposit rates. Each type operates under different rules, serves different customers, and faces different risks. Understanding the differences helps explain why your savings account and Goldman Sachs are both called banks but almost nothing else about them is the same.",
