    {
      "id": "what_this_means_for_you",
      "title": "What This Means for You",
      "summary": "Understanding how banks make money changes how you use them. Banks are not neutral services. They are businesses that profit from your behavior, and knowing which behaviors generate revenue for them helps you make choices that keep more money in your pocket. The interest rate spread means that shopping around for loan rates is worth the effort because even a small difference compounds into real savings. The fee structure means that choosing a bank with no maintenance fees and no overdraft charges can save hundreds of dollars a year. The equity and funding concepts mean you can recognize when a bank is taking on too much risk and protect your savings accordingly. Financial literacy does not require trusting banks less — it just means understanding the relationship clearly.",
